         <h1>Erwin Knoll, 63, Crusading Editor Of The Progressive </h1>
           <div class="row">
               <div class="col-md-10">
 					<p class="text-left">
<blue>1</blue>Erwin Knoll , the editor of The Progressive , an iconoclastic magazine that crusaded for civil liberties and against nuclear weapons and United States intervention abroad , died yesterday at his home in Madison , Wis . <br><blue>2</blue>He was 63 . <br><blue>3</blue>He died in his sleep , apparently of a heart attack , the Progressive said . <br><blue>4</blue>Mr. Knoll presided over a magazine that traces its roots to Robert M. La Follette Sr. , a combative maverick legislator in the early decades of the 20th century . <br><blue>5</blue>Mr. Knoll described The Progressive , which is based in Madison , as an " ecumenical journal of the American left . " <br><blue>6</blue>In 1979 , the year after he took over as editor , The Progressive became the first publication ever ordered by a Federal court not to print an article because of national security . <br><blue>7</blue>The Government had sought the order to prevent The Progressive from publishing an article called " The H-Bomb Secret , How We Got It -- Why We 're Telling It . " <br><blue>8</blue>Mr. Knoll said the article , which detailed the workings of a hydrogen bomb , was based solely on information in the public domain . <br><blue>9</blue>But the Justice Department contended that it violated the " restricted data " sections of the Atomic Energy Act of 1954 . <br><blue>10</blue>Judge Robert W. Warren of Federal District Court in Milwaukee issued an injunction barring publication , declaring that some of the information in the article could cause irreparable harm to the United States . <br><blue>11</blue>But the Justice Department dropped the case after it was challenged on a second front , when a local newspaper , The Madison Press Connection , printed a letter that the Government said also contained secret information about the bomb . <br><blue>12</blue>The Progressive subsequently printed its article as it had originally been set in type . <br><blue>13</blue>Born in Vienna , Mr. Knoll was brought to this country as a child . <br><blue>14</blue>He worked at The Washington Post from 1957 to 1963 , when he joined the Newhouse News Service as a White House correspondent . <br><blue>15</blue>He left five years later to become the Washington editor of The Progressive , and five years after that he moved to Madison as the editor . <br><blue>16</blue>When he died , he was working on a book about capital punishment , a practice he considered an abomination . <br><blue>17</blue>He was also an occasional commentator on the " MacNeil/Lehrer Newshour " on public television , He is survived by his wife , Doris ; two sons , David , of Madison , and Jonathan , of Boulder , Colo. , and a sister , Alice Allen , of Forest Hills , Queens . <br><hr><br><blue>1(19)</blue>: <m_str>He</m_str> (15_1) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (16_17) 	<m_str>He</m_str> (17_1) 	<m_str>He</m_str> (2_1) 	<m_str>Mr. Knoll</m_str> (13_5) 	<m_str>Mr. Knoll</m_str> (4_1) 	<m_str>Mr. Knoll</m_str> (8_1) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (6_7) 	<m_str>He</m_str> (14_1) 	<m_str>his</m_str> (1_31) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (16_2) 	<m_str>He</m_str> (17_17) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (15_20) 	<m_str>He</m_str> (3_1) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (16_5) 	<m_str>his</m_str> (17_21) 	<m_str>his</m_str> (3_4) 	<m_str>Mr. Knoll</m_str> (5_1) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (14_13) 	<br><blue>2(4)</blue>: <m_str>its article</m_str> (12_5) 	<m_str>an article</m_str> (6_28) 	<m_str>the article</m_str> (10_24) 	<m_str>the article , which detailed the workings of a hydrogen bomb</m_str> (8_4) 	<br><blue>3(3)</blue>: <m_str>Madison</m_str> (5_11) 	<m_str>Madison</m_str> (17_32) 	<m_str>Madison</m_str> (1_34) 	<br><blue>4(8)</blue>: <m_str>the Progressive</m_str> (3_13) 	<m_str>its</m_str> (12_5) 	<m_str>Progressive</m_str> (6_14) 	<m_str>it</m_str> (12_8) 	<m_str>The Progressive , which is based in Madison</m_str> (5_4) 	<m_str>The Progressive</m_str> (15_12) 	<m_str>its</m_str> (4_9) 	<m_str>The Progressive</m_str> (12_1) 	<br><blue>5(2)</blue>: <m_str>the bomb</m_str> (11_39) 	<m_s